---
name: kie-sfx
description: Generate a sound effect using Suno AI via the kie.ai API. Use when the user asks to generate, create, or make a sound effect or SFX. Also use when the user invokes /kie-sfx directly.
---

Generate a sound effect via the kie.ai Suno sounds API.

## Step 1 — Parse arguments

The user's args string is the sound description (e.g. "ancient stone door creaking open", "thunder crack with distant rumble"). Accept these optional flags:
- `--model <version>` — Suno model (default: `V5_5`). Options: `V5`, `V5_5`
- `--loop` — make the audio loop seamlessly (default: false)
- `--tempo <bpm>` — tempo in BPM, 1–300 (default: omit)
- `--key <key>` — musical key (e.g. `C`, `C#m`, `Dm`; default: `Any`)

## Step 2 — Check API key

Verify `KIE_API_KEY` is set. If not, tell the user to run: `export KIE_API_KEY=your_key_here`

## Step 3 — Submit the task

```bash
curl -s -X POST https://api.kie.ai/api/v1/generate/sounds \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $KIE_API_KEY" \
  -d '{
    "prompt": "<description>",
    "model": "<model>",
    "soundLoop": <true|false>
  }'
```

Include `"soundTempo": <bpm>` only if `--tempo` was provided. Include `"soundKey": "<key>"` only if `--key` was provided (omit for default `Any`).

Parse the response. If `code` is not `200`, show `msg` and stop. Extract `data.taskId`.

## Step 4 — Poll for completion

Poll every 10 seconds:

```bash
curl -s "https://api.kie.ai/api/v1/generate/record-info?taskId=<taskId>" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $KIE_API_KEY"
```

`data.status` values: `PENDING` → `FIRST_SUCCESS` → `SUCCESS`
Failure states: `CREATE_TASK_FAILED`, `GENERATE_AUDIO_FAILED`, `SENSITIVE_WORD_ERROR`

Show elapsed time each cycle. If status is a failure state, show `data.errorMessage` and stop.

## Step 5 — Return result

When `status` is `SUCCESS`, extract the audio URL from `data.response.sunoData[0].audioUrl`.

Display:
- The audio URL as a clickable link
- Description and settings used
- Task ID for reference

Ask if the user wants to download locally. If yes:

```bash
curl -L -o ~/Downloads/"sfx-$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S).mp3" "<audio_url>"
```

Report the saved path.
